english:
  title: On Reading Han Yu's Miscellaneous Remarks about Clouds and Dragons
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Han Yu speaks thus: "When the dragon exhales its breath, clouds are born. Yet clouds too possess a spiritual and wondrous nature. This spirituality comes through the dragon, yet the dragon's own spirituality is not granted by the clouds. Still, without riding upon clouds, how could the dragon manifest its miraculous power? What sustains it is of its own making."

    Such is Han's reasoning. Yet I say this: It is not the dragon alone. Man too follows this same principle. Why speak of the dragon and not extend it to man? Savoring Han's deeper intent, he uses the dragon as metaphor for man—and by speaking of the dragon rather than man directly, he leaves room for meaning to gather in silence, refusing to spill it out all at once.

    Consider lustrous prose and vigorous language—all spring forth from man himself. They shimmer into brocade and silk, rise stern as mountain peaks and precipices. Now stretched, now gathered; now crimson, now jade—all dance like clouds that swirl and scatter, massing in ten thousand forms. Truly these possess the spiritual and the wondrous. Yet this spirituality comes from man alone; the arts and talents do not confer it. Still, without the vessel of literary art and skill, man cannot manifest his spiritual splendor.

    Mark this well: the flawed dragon cannot summon clouds—only the true dragon can. Therefore, clouds do not grant the dragon its nature. This is clear. Yet without clouds to ride, the dragon cannot make its power shine. Similarly, the ordinary man cannot produce refined expression and vital breath; only the extraordinary man can. Thus neither can art perfect the man. This too is certain. Yet man without art cannot fully reveal his spiritual essence—just as the divine dragon and the poet share one transformation. Through this understanding, I unveil what Han left veiled.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 乖龍 (flawed dragon) contrasts with 神龍 (divine/true dragon)—a distinction between those without innate talent and those with exceptional gifts
  - key: ''
    value: The work engages with Han Yu's metaphor from his 'Miscellaneous Remarks on Clouds and Dragons,' extending it from dragons to human artistic creation
